Note:
Runa Standard Library: ArgParse Parser Module

Provides advanced argument parsing functionality including complex argument types,
custom parsers, and enterprise-grade parsing capabilities that exceed Python's argparse.

Features:
- Custom type parsers and converters
- Complex argument patterns and groups
- Advanced validation and error handling
- Interactive and AI-mode parsing
- Enterprise configuration integration
- Intelligent defaults and inference
:End Note

Import "argparse.argparse" as argparse

Note: Advanced Argument Types
Type FileArgument is ArgumentType with:
    must_exist as Boolean defaults to true
    readable as Boolean defaults to true
    writable as Boolean defaults to false
    executable as Boolean defaults to false
    extensions as List[String] defaults to list containing

Type DirectoryArgument is ArgumentType with:
    must_exist as Boolean defaults to true
    readable as Boolean defaults to true
    writable as Boolean defaults to false
    create_if_missing as Boolean defaults to false

Type RangeArgument is ArgumentType with:
    min_value as Optional[Number]
    max_value as Optional[Number]
    inclusive as Boolean defaults to true

Type RegexArgument is ArgumentType with:
    pattern as String
    flags as List[String] defaults to list containing

Type URLArgument is ArgumentType with:
    schemes as List[String] defaults to list containing "http", "https"
    allow_fragments as Boolean defaults to true
    allow_query as Boolean defaults to true

Type EmailArgument is ArgumentType with:
    validate_domain as Boolean defaults to true
    allow_local as Boolean defaults to false

Note: Advanced Parser Configuration
Type called "ParserConfig":
    case_sensitive as Boolean defaults to true
    allow_interspersed as Boolean defaults to true
    require_order as Boolean defaults to false
    auto_complete as Boolean defaults to false
    interactive_mode as Boolean defaults to false
    ai_suggestions as Boolean defaults to false
    strict_validation as Boolean defaults to true
    performance_mode as Boolean defaults to false

Type called "ValidationRule":
    rule_type as String
    parameters as Dictionary[String, Any]
    error_message as String
    severity as String defaults to "error"

Type called "ArgumentGroup":
    name as String
    title as String
    description as String
    mutually_exclusive as Boolean defaults to false
    required as Boolean defaults to false
    arguments as List[Argument]
    validation_rules as List[ValidationRule]

Note: Advanced Parser Functions
Process called "create_advanced_parser" that takes program_name as String and description as String and config as ParserConfig returns ArgumentParser:
    Let parser be argparse.create_parser with program_name as program_name and description as description
    Set parser["config"] to config
    Set parser["argument_groups"] to list containing
    Set parser["validation_rules"] to list containing
    Set parser["completion_cache"] to dictionary containing
    Return parser

Process called "add_argument_group" that takes parser as ArgumentParser and group as ArgumentGroup returns ArgumentParser:
    Add group to parser["argument_groups"]
    
    Note: Add all arguments from group to parser
    For each argument in group["arguments"]:
        Set argument["group"] to group["name"]
        Add argument to parser["arguments"]
    
    Return parser

Process called "add_validation_rule" that takes parser as ArgumentParser and rule as ValidationRule returns ArgumentParser:
    Add rule to parser["validation_rules"]
    Return parser

Process called "create_file_argument" that takes name as String and help as String and file_config as FileArgument returns Argument:
    Let argument be argparse.create_string_argument with name as name and help as help
    Set argument["type"] to FILE
    Set argument["file_config"] to file_config
    Set argument["validator"] to create_file_validator with config as file_config
    Return argument

Process called "create_directory_argument" that takes name as String and help as String and dir_config as DirectoryArgument returns Argument:
    Let argument be argparse.create_string_argument with name as name and help as help
    Set argument["type"] to DIRECTORY
    Set argument["dir_config"] to dir_config
    Set argument["validator"] to create_directory_validator with config as dir_config
    Return argument

Process called "create_range_argument" that takes name as String and help as String and range_config as RangeArgument returns Argument:
    Let argument be argparse.create_string_argument with name as name and help as help
    Set argument["type"] to CUSTOM with process as create_range_parser with config as range_config
    Set argument["range_config"] to range_config
    Set argument["validator"] to create_range_validator with config as range_config
    Return argument

Process called "create_regex_argument" that takes name as String and help as String and regex_config as RegexArgument returns Argument:
    Let argument be argparse.create_string_argument with name as name and help as help
    Set argument["type"] to CUSTOM with process as create_regex_parser with config as regex_config
    Set argument["regex_config"] to regex_config
    Set argument["validator"] to create_regex_validator with config as regex_config
    Return argument

Process called "create_url_argument" that takes name as String and help as String and url_config as URLArgument returns Argument:
    Let argument be argparse.create_string_argument with name as name and help as help
    Set argument["type"] to CUSTOM with process as create_url_parser with config as url_config
    Set argument["url_config"] to url_config
    Set argument["validator"] to create_url_validator with config as url_config
    Return argument

Process called "create_email_argument" that takes name as String and help as String and email_config as EmailArgument returns Argument:
    Let argument be argparse.create_string_argument with name as name and help as help
    Set argument["type"] to CUSTOM with process as create_email_parser with config as email_config
    Set argument["email_config"] to email_config
    Set argument["validator"] to create_email_validator with config as email_config
    Return argument

Note: Validation Functions
Process called "create_file_validator" that takes config as FileArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "validate_file" that takes value as String returns Boolean:
        Note: Check if file exists
        If config["must_exist"]:
            If not file_exists with path as value:
                Return false
        
        Note: Check file permissions
        If config["readable"] and not file_readable with path as value:
            Return false
        
        If config["writable"] and not file_writable with path as value:
            Return false
        
        If config["executable"] and not file_executable with path as value:
            Return false
        
        Note: Check file extensions
        If length of config["extensions"] is greater than 0:
            Let file_extension be get_file_extension with path as value
            If file_extension is not in config["extensions"]:
                Return false
        
        Return true

Process called "create_directory_validator" that takes config as DirectoryArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "validate_directory" that takes value as String returns Boolean:
        Note: Check if directory exists
        If config["must_exist"]:
            If not directory_exists with path as value:
                If config["create_if_missing"]:
                    Try:
                        create_directory with path as value
                    Catch:
                        Return false
                Otherwise:
                    Return false
        
        Note: Check directory permissions
        If config["readable"] and not directory_readable with path as value:
            Return false
        
        If config["writable"] and not directory_writable with path as value:
            Return false
        
        Return true

Process called "create_range_validator" that takes config as RangeArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "validate_range" that takes value as Number returns Boolean:
        If config["min_value"] is not None:
            If config["inclusive"]:
                If value is less than config["min_value"]:
                    Return false
            Otherwise:
                If value is less than or equal to config["min_value"]:
                    Return false
        
        If config["max_value"] is not None:
            If config["inclusive"]:
                If value is greater than config["max_value"]:
                    Return false
            Otherwise:
                If value is greater than or equal to config["max_value"]:
                    Return false
        
        Return true

Process called "create_regex_validator" that takes config as RegexArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "validate_regex" that takes value as String returns Boolean:
        Try:
            Let match_result be regex_match with pattern as config["pattern"] and text as value and flags as config["flags"]
            Return match_result is not None
        Catch:
            Return false

Process called "create_url_validator" that takes config as URLArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "validate_url" that takes value as String returns Boolean:
        Try:
            Let parsed_url be parse_url with url as value
            
            Note: Check scheme
            If length of config["schemes"] is greater than 0:
                If parsed_url["scheme"] is not in config["schemes"]:
                    Return false
            
            Note: Check fragments and query parameters
            If not config["allow_fragments"] and parsed_url["fragment"] is not None:
                Return false
            
            If not config["allow_query"] and parsed_url["query"] is not None:
                Return false
            
            Return true
        Catch:
            Return false

Process called "create_email_validator" that takes config as EmailArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "validate_email" that takes value as String returns Boolean:
        Try:
            Note: Basic email validation
            If not "@" is in value:
                Return false
            
            Let parts be split string value by "@"
            If length of parts is not equal to 2:
                Return false
            
            Let local_part be parts at index 0
            Let domain_part be parts at index 1
            
            If local_part is equal to "" or domain_part is equal to "":
                Return false
            
            Note: Check local part restrictions
            If not config["allow_local"] and domain_part is equal to "localhost":
                Return false
            
            Note: Validate domain if required
            If config["validate_domain"]:
                If not is_valid_domain with domain as domain_part:
                    Return false
            
            Return true
        Catch:
            Return false

Note: Type Parser Functions
Process called "create_range_parser" that takes config as RangeArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "parse_range_value" that takes value as String returns Number:
        Try:
            If "." is in value:
                Let result be value as Float
                Return result
            Otherwise:
                Let result be value as Integer
                Return result
        Catch:
            Return None

Process called "create_regex_parser" that takes config as RegexArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "parse_regex_value" that takes value as String returns String:
        Try:
            Let match_result be regex_match with pattern as config["pattern"] and text as value and flags as config["flags"]
            If match_result is not None:
                Return value
            Otherwise:
                Return None
        Catch:
            Return None

Process called "create_url_parser" that takes config as URLArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "parse_url_value" that takes value as String returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
        Try:
            Let parsed_url be parse_url with url as value
            Return parsed_url
        Catch:
            Return None

Process called "create_email_parser" that takes config as EmailArgument returns Process:
    Return Process called "parse_email_value" that takes value as String returns Dictionary[String, String]:
        Try:
            Let parts be split string value by "@"
            Return dictionary with:
                "local" as parts at index 0
                "domain" as parts at index 1
                "full" as value
        Catch:
            Return None

Note: Interactive Parsing
Process called "parse_interactive" that takes parser as ArgumentParser returns ArgParseResult:
    Let result_values be dictionary containing
    
    Display "Interactive argument configuration for " plus parser["program_name"]
    Display parser["description"]
    Display ""
    
    For each argument in parser["arguments"]:
        If not argument["hidden"]:
            Let prompt_text be argument["name"]
            If argument["help"] is not None:
                Set prompt_text to prompt_text plus " (" plus argument["help"] plus ")"
            
            If argument["required"]:
                Set prompt_text to prompt_text plus " [required]"
            
            If argument["default"] is not None:
                Set prompt_text to prompt_text plus " [default: " plus argument["default"] plus "]"
            
            Set prompt_text to prompt_text plus ": "
            
            Let user_input be prompt_user with message as prompt_text
            
            If user_input is equal to "" and argument["default"] is not None:
                Set result_values[argument["name"]] to argument["default"]
            Otherwise if user_input is not equal to "":
                Let converted_value be argparse.convert_type with value as user_input and arg_type as argument["type"]
                If converted_value is not None:
                    Set result_values[argument["name"]] to converted_value
                Otherwise:
                    Display "Invalid value, using default"
                    If argument["default"] is not None:
                        Set result_values[argument["name"]] to argument["default"]
            Otherwise if argument["required"]:
                Display "Required argument cannot be empty"
                Return ParseError with message as "Missing required argument: " plus argument["name"] and code as "MISSING_REQUIRED"
    
    Return ParseSuccess with values as result_values and command as None

Note: AI-Assisted Parsing
Process called "parse_with_ai_suggestions" that takes parser as ArgumentParser and argv as List[String] returns ArgParseResult:
    Note: First try normal parsing
    Let normal_result be argparse.parse_args with parser as parser and argv as argv
    
    If normal_result is ParseSuccess:
        Return normal_result
    
    Note: If parsing failed, provide AI suggestions
    Display "Parsing failed. Here are some suggestions:"
    
    Note: Suggest corrections for common mistakes
    Let suggestions be generate_ai_suggestions with parser as parser and argv as argv and error as normal_result
    For each suggestion in suggestions:
        Display "  - " plus suggestion
    
    Note: Offer to try interactive mode
    Display ""
    Let use_interactive be prompt_user with message as "Would you like to use interactive mode? (y/n): "
    If use_interactive is equal to "y" or use_interactive is equal to "yes":
        Return parse_interactive with parser as parser
    
    Return normal_result

Process called "generate_ai_suggestions" that takes parser as ArgumentParser and argv as List[String] and error as ArgParseResult returns List[String]:
    Let suggestions be list containing
    
    Note: Analyze the error and provide suggestions
    If error is ParseError:
        Let error_code be error["code"]
        Let error_message be error["message"]
        
        If error_code is equal to "UNKNOWN_ARGUMENT":
            Note: Suggest similar argument names
            Let unknown_arg be extract_unknown_argument with message as error_message
            Let similar_args be find_similar_arguments with parser as parser and arg as unknown_arg
            For each similar_arg in similar_args:
                Add "Did you mean '--" plus similar_arg plus "'?" to suggestions
        
        Otherwise if error_code is equal to "MISSING_VALUE":
            Add "Make sure to provide a value after the argument" to suggestions
        
        Otherwise if error_code is equal to "MISSING_REQUIRED":
            Add "All required arguments must be provided" to suggestions
            Let required_args be get_required_arguments with parser as parser
            Add "Required arguments: " plus required_args to suggestions
    
    Return suggestions

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "prompt_user" that takes message as String returns String:
    Display message without newline
    Let input be read_user_input
    Return input

Process called "find_similar_arguments" that takes parser as ArgumentParser and arg as String returns List[String]:
    Let similar_args be list containing
    
    For each argument in parser["arguments"]:
        Let similarity be calculate_string_similarity with str1 as arg and str2 as argument["name"]
        If similarity is greater than 0.6:
            Add argument["name"] to similar_args
    
    Return similar_args

Process called "calculate_string_similarity" that takes str1 as String and str2 as String returns Float:
    Note: Simple Levenshtein distance-based similarity
    Let max_len be maximum of length of str1 and length of str2
    If max_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1.0
    
    Let distance be levenshtein_distance with s1 as str1 and s2 as str2
    Return 1.0 minus distance divided by max_len

Process called "levenshtein_distance" that takes s1 as String and s2 as String returns Integer:
    Let len1 be length of s1
    Let len2 be length of s2
    
    If len1 is equal to 0:
        Return len2
    If len2 is equal to 0:
        Return len1
    
    Note: Create distance matrix
    Let matrix be create_2d_array with rows as len1 plus 1 and cols as len2 plus 1
    
    Note: Initialize first row and column
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than or equal to len1:
        Set matrix[i][0] to i
        Set i to i plus 1
    
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than or equal to len2:
        Set matrix[0][j] to j
        Set j to j plus 1
    
    Note: Fill the matrix
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than or equal to len1:
        Set j to 1
        While j is less than or equal to len2:
            Let cost be 0
            If s1 at index i minus 1 is not equal to s2 at index j minus 1:
                Set cost to 1
            
            Let deletion be matrix[i minus 1][j] plus 1
            Let insertion be matrix[i][j minus 1] plus 1
            Let substitution be matrix[i minus 1][j minus 1] plus cost
            
            Set matrix[i][j] to minimum of deletion, insertion, substitution
            Set j to j plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    
    Return matrix[len1][len2]